Anonymous Sun 09 Jan 2022 01:53:19 No.44600657 Report
Quoted By: >>44600803 >>44600884 >>44601044
>>44599717
May want to phrase that
> foxes "mate for life"

There are a number of factors but, when a fox loses a mate, especially young vixens may take another mate. It can be highly contextual, such as local fox population density. If there's open territory with rich food availability (one example), a young vixen may be approachable by a male wandering into her territory. The biological need to perpetuate the species can override some natural tendencies. Focus on the term "tendency" here. It's not a rule or a law, it's a generalization from statistical observation. If a vixen loses her mate, she might skip one breeding heat without taking another. By the time she begins her 2nd or 3rd, she might be receptive to a suitor, especially if he doesn't have many other options & persistently courts her. If there's more than one interested male, they will compete for her and the hormonal breeding pressure will often sway her.

Reverse some of the circumstances, then the generalization may prevail. Such as an older vixen that had 3 or 4 litters with a steady mate, loses him, and finds herself in a territory surrounded/infiltrated by a vigorous fox population putting stress on food resources. She will have much less tendency to to accept a new mate.

My understanding is that this holds similar for males, but maybe with less intensity. A male that has never had a mate is pretty ready to take on any female that is receptive, or even doesn't resist too much. There's that famous documentary from a couple years ago where a young male breeds his own mother. She resists him "somewhat," but he insists in what amounts to borderline rape. In that situation, his father was still alive but older. He just happened to not be present at the time, but trotted into the scene while the son was still knotted to his mother. Later the original pair stayed together and the son went off to find another mate.

Given the apocalyptic setting you envision, these are significant factors to consider.
